## When to send a health check

Paired with R5 (Customer Touch Monitor) or R22 (Quarterly HQ Touchpoint) routine output. The routine flags customers with no touch in N+ days; this template is the response.

| Silence | Hook style | Tone |
|---|---|---|
| 30–60 days | Direct check-in (Option D) | Warm, low-key |
| 60–120 days | Industry-signal hook (Option A) | Re-establish relevance |
| 120–365 days | Conference or capability hook (Option B/C) | "Genuine reason to be in touch" |
| 365+ days (Aramco HQ-style relationship) | Capability + offer to meet (Option B/C) | Treat as semi-cold; show what's new |

The hook is critical. A health-check email without a hook reads as "I'm chasing you" — recipient ignores. With a hook, it reads as "Maaz had a reason to think of me" — recipient engages.

---

## Operator review checklist before send

- [ ] Last touch date verified (search Sent items, calendar, chats for the actual last interaction)
- [ ] Last topic accurately summarized (not paraphrased from memory)
- [ ] Hook is real — don't invent industry news; don't claim conference attendance unless confirmed
- [ ] No false urgency ("would love to reconnect ASAP")
- [ ] SRE internal owner CC'd (so internal team sees the re-engagement)
- [ ] Customer contact email still current (not stale — verify against LinkedIn or recent inbound)
- [ ] No reference to confidential / sale-process content
- [ ] Length 60–100 words

**Approved by**: ______________ **Date**: __________

